    id: 'Y8N17',
    title: 'Every Drop Counts: The Case for Clean Water',
    type: 'nonfiction',
    source: 'Original (factually grounded)',
    text: 'Imagine walking for three hours every morning before you eat breakfast, before you go to school, before you do anything else. Not for exercise. Not for pleasure. But because the nearest source of water is six kilometres away, and someone in your household has to fetch it. For hundreds of millions of people around the world, this is not a hypothetical scenario — it is simply Tuesday.\n\nAccording to UNICEF, approximately 703 million people currently lack access to safe drinking water close to home. That figure is almost impossible to picture, so try this instead: it is roughly ten times the population of the United Kingdom. Every single one of those people faces daily decisions that most of us never have to make — between drinking water that may make them ill and drinking no water at all.\n\nThe consequences extend far beyond thirst. Waterborne diseases such as cholera and typhoid kill more than 800,000 people each year — the vast majority of them children under the age of five. Girls in particular bear the burden of water collection in many communities, meaning hours spent fetching water are hours not spent in school. The World Health Organisation estimates that for every pound invested in clean water infrastructure, up to eight pounds is returned in economic productivity. Clean water, in other words, is not a charitable nicety. It is one of the most efficient investments a society can make.\n\nOur charity, WaterFirst, has been working in sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia since 2009. In that time, we have helped construct over 1,400 wells and install rainwater harvesting systems in more than 600 schools. We have trained local engineers, supported women-led maintenance committees, and watched communities transform within months of gaining reliable water access. School attendance rises. Child mortality falls. Women start businesses. The change is not slow or incremental — it is immediate and visible.\n\nBut we cannot do this without you. Each five-pound monthly donation funds the maintenance of one well for an entire year. Twenty pounds a month provides clean water for a classroom of thirty children. And a one-off gift of one hundred and fifty pounds contributes to the cost of drilling a new borehole that will serve a village of five hundred people for a decade.\n\nYou may feel that these are large numbers, or that your individual contribution cannot possibly make a difference when the scale of the problem is so vast. We understand that feeling. But consider: 703 million people did not lose access to clean water all at once. It happened one community at a time. And it will be solved one community at a time — starting, perhaps, with the one your donation reaches today.\n\nThe water crisis is not inevitable. It is not an act of nature. It is the result of underinvestment, inequality, and inaction — all of which can be reversed. You have the power to be part of that reversal. Please donate today at waterfirst.org.uk, or call our freephone number to speak to one of our team. Every drop counts. So does every pound.',
