        guidance: 'Indicative content: identify methods AND effects with short quotations. Credit: metaphor \'erupted\' conveys sudden, explosive arrival; list of negatives (\'no time for\', \'no patience for\', \'no interest whatsoever\') uses anaphora to capture punk\'s aggressive rejection of existing norms; simile \'like a bucket of cold water\' suggests punk as shock and necessary awakening; the word \'democratisation\' elevates punk from vandalism to political act; contrast between \'anger\' and \'answers\' shows balanced judgement; the contemporary references (Billie Eilish, Dave) make the historical analysis feel relevant. L4: perceptive comment on effect. L3: clear comment. L2: some comment. L1: simple identification.',
        model: 'Model answer: The writer uses the verb \'erupted\' in the opening sentence to convey the sudden, violent arrival of punk, suggesting an unstoppable natural force rather than a calculated movement. The repeated use of \'no\' — \'no time for\', \'no patience for\', \'no interest whatsoever\' — creates an accumulating sense of confrontation, each refusal adding to the impression of a movement defined entirely by what it opposed. The simile \'like a bucket of cold water\' positions punk as a necessary shock to a complacent industry, implying that the discomfort it caused was a feature rather than a flaw. These choices together make punk sound not merely noisy but purposeful.'
